WEBVTT

00:02.002 --> 00:03.037
- You know, I was thinking
maybe tonight, we try

00:03.071 --> 00:06.040
that tofu with peppers dish
we were reading about.

00:06.074 --> 00:08.008
- Ambitious. I like it.
- Okay, uh, fennel seeds.

00:08.042 --> 00:09.977
- Go.
- We need tofu.

00:10.010 --> 00:13.547
We need two red
and yellow bell peppers.

00:13.581 --> 00:15.015
(ominous music pounds)

00:15.049 --> 00:16.850
Oh...

00:16.884 --> 00:19.153
- Um, is there any way
that somebody could be, like

00:19.187 --> 00:20.821
watching us, is that a thing?
- What?

00:20.854 --> 00:22.156
*

00:22.190 --> 00:23.824
Oh, Christ, they found me.

00:23.857 --> 00:26.227
- What's going on?
- Uh, do you trust me?

00:26.260 --> 00:27.895
- Yes?
- Run!

00:27.928 --> 00:30.898
(intense percussive music)

00:30.931 --> 00:33.234
*

00:35.035 --> 00:36.204
(grunts)

00:44.912 --> 00:47.248
(tires screech)

00:47.281 --> 00:49.850
- Oh! What's the matter
with you? Are you nuts?

00:49.883 --> 00:51.018
- (grunts)

00:51.051 --> 00:53.053
*

00:53.087 --> 00:54.355
(thud)

00:54.388 --> 00:56.257
(groans)
- Josh!

00:56.290 --> 00:58.092
- Jesus Christ.
- Honey, are you okay?

00:58.126 --> 01:00.094
- (moans)
- Who are you?

01:00.128 --> 01:03.030
- I'm Josh's stepdad, Tom.

01:03.063 --> 01:04.098
- Oh, my God, hi.

01:04.132 --> 01:05.533
- Bet that was hard to tell

01:05.566 --> 01:07.101
with this new hat
I'm trying out, huh?

01:07.135 --> 01:08.236
- Tom, what do you want?

01:08.269 --> 01:09.570
- Your mother sent me.

01:09.603 --> 01:11.572
Ever since
you two started dating,

01:11.605 --> 01:13.707
you've been on
her Most Wanted list.

01:13.741 --> 01:16.210
You can't get away
with having a new girlfriend

01:16.244 --> 01:18.546
and not bringing her by
for dinner.

01:18.579 --> 01:20.748
- Uh, yeah, you're right.
I'm sorry.

01:20.781 --> 01:22.750
(groans) Uh, well, see,
the thing about it is,

01:22.783 --> 01:24.718
this week, I--
it's pretty hectic,

01:24.752 --> 01:26.420
work-wise, it's just
that time of year--

01:26.454 --> 01:27.421
(blow lands)
Ah!

01:27.455 --> 01:28.722
Okay.
(winded gasp)

01:28.756 --> 01:30.591
Not just work,
there's also--we have

01:30.624 --> 01:32.593
out-of-town friends visiting
that don't really know this--

01:32.626 --> 01:34.061
(blow lands)
Ah! Jesus Christ.

01:34.094 --> 01:35.229
- Josh?
- All right, stop.

01:35.263 --> 01:37.064
Just--please.

01:37.097 --> 01:38.732
Stop hitting me.
Look, we'll come for dinner.

01:38.766 --> 01:40.268
(upbeat music)
- Yeah, yeah, we can't wait.

01:40.301 --> 01:41.769
- Okeydoke!
We'll see you Friday.

01:41.802 --> 01:42.770
- Okay.

01:42.803 --> 01:44.104
(blow lands)
(gasps)

01:44.138 --> 01:47.107
(downtempo electronic music)

01:47.141 --> 01:48.108
*

01:48.142 --> 01:49.443
- Ah!

01:49.477 --> 01:52.646
*

01:52.680 --> 01:54.748
- (squeaks)

01:54.782 --> 01:56.450
*

01:56.484 --> 01:57.785
- (growls)

01:57.818 --> 01:59.820
*

02:14.134 --> 02:15.102
(upbeat music)

02:15.135 --> 02:17.104
- I am so excited.

02:17.137 --> 02:18.972
I finally get to meet
the famous Patti Greenberg.

02:19.006 --> 02:20.441
What you doing, Josh?

02:20.474 --> 02:21.475
- (pained chuckle)

02:21.509 --> 02:23.444
Uh, well, I read online

02:23.477 --> 02:25.779
uh, that yoga relaxes you,
so I tried doing yoga,

02:25.813 --> 02:27.448
but I injured myself
pretty badly.

02:27.481 --> 02:28.949
So now I'm just
trying to make it better.

02:28.982 --> 02:30.284
- Josh, why are you so nervous?

02:30.318 --> 02:31.652
- Uh, look,

02:31.685 --> 02:33.621
Lucy, I know
how awesome you are.

02:33.654 --> 02:36.490
But my mother
is a very particular person.

02:36.524 --> 02:38.626
And her house has, like,

02:38.659 --> 02:40.528
a million weird
little rules.

02:40.561 --> 02:42.496
- Josh, it's totally fine.

02:42.530 --> 02:43.831
It's gonna be cool,
we'll just--

02:43.864 --> 02:45.132
uh, we'll just
feel it out, okay?

02:45.165 --> 02:46.467
- You'll just feel it out?

02:46.500 --> 02:47.801
Are you crazy?
- They're just parents.

02:47.835 --> 02:49.136
It's fine.
- You don't understand.

02:49.169 --> 02:50.371
You don't know
what you're walking into.

02:50.404 --> 02:53.474
You don't know what
these people are capable of!

02:53.507 --> 02:55.476
I--I don't know how
to describe it to you, but...

02:55.509 --> 02:56.510
(dramatic music)

02:56.544 --> 02:57.845
But I know someone who does.

02:57.878 --> 02:59.012
Come on.

02:59.046 --> 03:00.648
*

03:00.681 --> 03:01.815
- You've come
to the right place.

03:01.849 --> 03:03.817
- Yeah, Liz is the, uh,

03:03.851 --> 03:05.653
world's preeminent authority
on our parents.

03:05.686 --> 03:07.388
Nobody's been
studying them longer.

03:07.421 --> 03:09.523
- I lived among them
for 18 years.

03:09.557 --> 03:11.225
Theirs is a crude
and primitive world,

03:11.259 --> 03:13.361
but in some ways,
it's beautiful.

03:13.394 --> 03:14.528
- Sounds fascinating.

03:14.562 --> 03:16.830
- But it's also very dangerous.

03:16.864 --> 03:19.233
They have many baffling
rituals and social customs

03:19.267 --> 03:20.868
that must be followed to a T.

03:20.901 --> 03:21.902
- Or what?

03:21.935 --> 03:23.504
- They'll label you as...

03:23.537 --> 03:25.739
"a handful"
or "not right for Joshy."

03:25.773 --> 03:27.741
- But we are not gonna
let that happen.

03:27.775 --> 03:29.877
Uh, right, Liz?
- That's right.

03:29.910 --> 03:31.712
Let's start with
the clippings ritual.

03:31.745 --> 03:33.514
Now, Lucy, if I were
to hand you this,

03:33.547 --> 03:34.848
what would you do with it?

03:34.882 --> 03:37.418
- (muttering)
- It's okay.

03:41.722 --> 03:43.891
- Oh, no.
- 'Cause it's garbage, right?

03:43.924 --> 03:45.726
- Yes.
To us, it is garbage.

03:45.759 --> 03:48.729
It's a random, useless article
from an old local newspaper.

03:48.762 --> 03:51.432
But in Mom and Tom's world,
that was considered a gift.

03:51.465 --> 03:53.233
- (inhales sharply)
So I should read it?

03:53.267 --> 03:54.702
- 'Course not.
You must simply recite

03:54.735 --> 03:57.204
the proper
ceremonial response.

03:57.237 --> 03:58.706
"I look forward
to reading this."

03:58.739 --> 04:01.542
- "I look forward
to reading this."

04:01.575 --> 04:02.876
- Yeah, that's good, good.

04:02.910 --> 04:04.278
That's good.
- Yeah? Okay.

04:04.312 --> 04:05.413
*

04:05.446 --> 04:06.714
- Taste it.

04:06.747 --> 04:08.716
(music pounds)

04:08.749 --> 04:10.418
- (gags)

04:10.451 --> 04:12.252
- (gags)
- It's called "ranch dressing."

04:12.286 --> 04:13.787
- I did not like that.
- No, none of us do.

04:13.821 --> 04:15.389
It's very thick.

04:15.423 --> 04:16.890
You just have to pretend.

04:16.924 --> 04:18.792
- Ranch is central
to Mom and Tom's diet.

04:18.826 --> 04:20.561
To them,
it's like liquid gold.

04:20.594 --> 04:22.596
I once watched them
take down an entire jar

04:22.630 --> 04:24.432
during an episode
of Blue Bloods.

04:24.465 --> 04:25.466
- Whoa.

04:25.499 --> 04:28.402
- Say you're washing your hands
before dinner.

04:28.436 --> 04:30.804
Which towel would you use
to dry them?

04:30.838 --> 04:32.105
(suspenseful music)
- I guess...

04:32.139 --> 04:33.941
Halloween, 'cause
it's the lesser holiday?

04:33.974 --> 04:35.242
- Shit. Shit.
- What?

04:35.275 --> 04:36.410
- The answer is neither.

04:36.444 --> 04:38.579
Patti and Tom
still follow Towel Law.

04:38.612 --> 04:40.614
This is the outdated practice
of displaying

04:40.648 --> 04:43.317
holiday-themed towels
solely to gaze upon.

04:43.351 --> 04:44.418
- So where do you
dry your hands?

04:44.452 --> 04:45.919
- On your jeans or whatever.

04:45.953 --> 04:47.087
- Why don't they just
put, like,

04:47.120 --> 04:48.155
another towel
in the bathroom?

04:48.188 --> 04:49.156
- You're still trying to force

04:49.189 --> 04:51.091
our way of thinking
onto their world.

04:51.124 --> 04:52.660
- Oh, my God, I hope
I remember all this.

04:52.693 --> 04:54.595
- You'll know it went well
if she lets you look

04:54.628 --> 04:57.264
at the family photo album;
it's their most sacred object.

04:57.297 --> 04:58.932
- Okay, it's 4:00 p.m.
We gotta--we gotta go.

04:58.966 --> 05:00.468
- I thought we were
going for dinner.

05:00.501 --> 05:01.769
- 4:00 p.m. is dinner.

05:01.802 --> 05:03.437
(dramatic music pounds)
Damn it. Shit.

05:03.471 --> 05:04.638
- Hi!
- Hi.

05:04.672 --> 05:06.273
- Get in here, you kids.
- (chuckling)

05:06.306 --> 05:07.274
- Hi, I'm Lucy.
Nice to meet you.

05:07.307 --> 05:08.442
- Hi.

05:08.476 --> 05:09.643
- Hi, how are you?
- Hi!

05:09.677 --> 05:11.445
- Hi. Lucy--no?
- (gibbering)

05:11.479 --> 05:13.681
- Okay, oh, there we go.
That's good. Hi.

05:13.714 --> 05:15.282
- Oh!

05:15.315 --> 05:17.451
Josh told me
you were a graphic designer.

05:17.485 --> 05:19.953
So I wanted to give you this.

05:19.987 --> 05:22.322
- Thank you.
That's--thank you.

05:22.356 --> 05:24.792
Uh, "Art Museum Attendance
in Illinois Remains

05:24.825 --> 05:26.794
the Same as Last Year."

05:26.827 --> 05:30.798
(tense exotic music)

05:30.831 --> 05:32.633
I--I look forward
to reading this.

05:32.666 --> 05:33.667
- (exhales)

05:33.701 --> 05:36.670
(upbeat pop music)

05:36.704 --> 05:39.339
*

05:56.023 --> 05:57.991
- And Frank's sons...
- Mm-hmm.

05:58.025 --> 06:00.528
- Danny and Jamie...
- Uh, Danny--uh, Jamie Jr.

06:00.561 --> 06:02.229
- Jamie Jr.
- Right.

06:02.262 --> 06:03.831
- He's a big man.
- That's the cousin Jamie.

06:03.864 --> 06:04.998
- Oh, that's the cousin Jamie.
- There's Jamie,

06:05.032 --> 06:06.500
Jamie Jr., and Cousin Jamie.

06:06.534 --> 06:07.535
- Okay.
- And you can tell--

06:07.568 --> 06:09.002
and Jamie Jr. you can tell

06:09.036 --> 06:10.571
'cause he's got red hair
like his dad.

06:10.604 --> 06:12.005
- That's right.
- Yeah.

06:12.039 --> 06:13.340
- Okay. All right.
- Yeah.

06:13.373 --> 06:15.843
- So they're all NYPD.

06:15.876 --> 06:17.344
- Yeah.
- Well, I, for one,

06:17.377 --> 06:18.912
never mind a refresher
on the family tree

06:18.946 --> 06:20.347
of the show Blue Bloods.

06:20.380 --> 06:21.515
- No, that was a great story.

06:21.549 --> 06:24.017
- We had fun telling it!
- Yes.

06:24.051 --> 06:26.253
- I think this was
the best dinner ever.

06:26.286 --> 06:27.555
- I agree.
- Yeah.

06:27.588 --> 06:30.257
- And, as a matter of fact,
Lucy,

06:30.290 --> 06:32.025
I rarely do this, but

06:32.059 --> 06:33.761
would you have any interest

06:33.794 --> 06:36.930
in seeing
the family photo album?

06:36.964 --> 06:38.365
(tender music)

06:38.398 --> 06:39.533
- Yeah.

06:39.567 --> 06:40.734
Yeah, that'd--that'd be great.

06:40.768 --> 06:42.536
*

06:42.570 --> 06:44.037
- Thank you guys, love ya.
- Buh-bye.

06:44.071 --> 06:45.873
- Thank you, bye-bye.
- We'll see you soon.

06:45.906 --> 06:47.374
- Buh-bye.
- Buh-bye now.

06:47.407 --> 06:48.576
- That was really fun.

06:48.609 --> 06:50.944
- Ohh!
- Oh, Jesus...(muttering)

06:50.978 --> 06:52.379
(gentle guitar music)

06:52.412 --> 06:53.380
(both exhale)

06:53.413 --> 06:54.381
- We did it.
We made it.

06:54.414 --> 06:55.716
We survived.
- Yeah.

06:55.749 --> 06:57.384
- Like, I know my mother
can be a bit much.

06:57.417 --> 06:58.452
But we came out here.
- Mm-hmm.

06:58.486 --> 06:59.753
- They liked you,
and now,

06:59.787 --> 07:01.388
we don't have to
see her again till

07:01.421 --> 07:02.890
spring at the earliest.
- (laughs)

07:02.923 --> 07:04.892
Okay.
- So...

07:04.925 --> 07:06.460
I--I spoke too soon.

07:06.494 --> 07:08.629
- Yoo-hoo!

07:08.662 --> 07:10.764
You know,
I was just telling Tom

07:10.798 --> 07:12.600
that I had such
a good time tonight

07:12.633 --> 07:14.234
that I think

07:14.267 --> 07:16.069
we have to
do this again soon.

07:16.103 --> 07:17.905
- Yeah, yeah, definitely.
- Absolutely.

07:17.938 --> 07:19.406
- Yeah, at--at some point.
- Yeah.

07:19.439 --> 07:21.074
- How about this Saturday?

07:21.108 --> 07:22.743
- You--you mean tomorrow?

07:22.776 --> 07:24.745
- Yeah.

07:24.778 --> 07:26.480
- Uh, well, uh, you know,

07:26.514 --> 07:28.782
as much as we'd love to, uh,

07:28.816 --> 07:32.920
wake up and drive all the way
back out here tomorrow

07:32.953 --> 07:34.922
and just do everything
we did today,

07:34.955 --> 07:37.758
um, we--we actually kind of
had a bit of a day

07:37.791 --> 07:39.760
planned in the city, so...

07:39.793 --> 07:41.328
- Well, then
I'll come to you.

07:41.361 --> 07:43.430
- You--what?
- Big day in the city?

07:43.463 --> 07:45.098
Can't wait!
- Oh.

07:45.132 --> 07:46.600
- I'll see you tomorrow.
- All right, see you.

07:46.634 --> 07:48.101
- See you tomorrow.
- See you tomorrow.

07:48.135 --> 07:49.837
- Bye-bye, see ya.
- Bye. That was great.

07:49.870 --> 07:51.839
*

07:51.872 --> 07:54.474
- Bye. Yep.
Bye.

07:54.508 --> 07:56.510
*

08:01.515 --> 08:04.284
(gentle upbeat music)

08:04.317 --> 08:07.988
- Oh, Tom, it's been
the most wonderful day.

08:08.021 --> 08:10.190
Well, we hit the aquarium

08:10.223 --> 08:12.025
and then the wax museum,

08:12.059 --> 08:15.028
and then there was
a bus tour of old churches.

08:15.062 --> 08:17.164
- She's never gonna
leave us alone.

08:17.197 --> 08:18.966
- Actually,
she might if you just

08:18.999 --> 08:20.634
told her that
you need some space, maybe.

08:20.668 --> 08:22.335
- No, I--I'm just
trying to, like, avoid

08:22.369 --> 08:24.471
a proper confrontation
with her.

08:24.504 --> 08:26.506
- Okay, so...

08:26.540 --> 08:28.008
What are you guys thinking?

08:28.041 --> 08:30.510
Should we go out
for dinner or

08:30.544 --> 08:33.714
you want to squeeze in
one more bus tour first?

08:33.747 --> 08:35.215
- Hmm.
Bus tour?

08:35.248 --> 08:37.017
What do you--what--
what's your instinct?

08:37.050 --> 08:39.219
Actually, you know,
Mom, Lucy and I

08:39.252 --> 08:42.022
are both, uh,
pretty tuckered out

08:42.055 --> 08:43.390
so I think
we're just gonna...

08:43.423 --> 08:45.158
- (yawning) We're pretty tired.
- Crash.

08:45.192 --> 08:46.560
- It's only 6:00.

08:46.594 --> 08:49.229
- Nevertheless, uh,
we are going to sleep now,

08:49.262 --> 08:51.331
so I think you, maybe, just

08:51.364 --> 08:54.334
should probably...
(mumbles)

08:54.367 --> 08:56.737
- Say no more.
I get it.

08:56.770 --> 08:59.239
You guys head off to bed,

08:59.272 --> 09:02.242
and I'll just sit tight.

09:02.275 --> 09:04.177
Don't you worry about me.

09:04.211 --> 09:06.079
I'll be fine.

09:08.381 --> 09:09.583
- It's very bright.

09:09.617 --> 09:11.018
- I know.

09:11.051 --> 09:12.519
Just squint hard.

09:12.552 --> 09:14.254
We'll be asleep
in a matter of hours.

09:14.287 --> 09:16.089
- Josh, this isn't good.

09:16.123 --> 09:17.625
She's starting to
get obsessed with us.

09:22.395 --> 09:24.031
- It'll all be fine.

09:24.064 --> 09:25.365
- (laughing)

09:25.398 --> 09:26.600
- Yoo-hoo!
- Jesus.

09:26.634 --> 09:28.602
- It's me,
your number one fan.

09:28.636 --> 09:30.203
- Yep, why--what are you--
why are you here?

09:30.237 --> 09:31.238
What are you doing here?

09:31.271 --> 09:32.706
- Can I get a picture?

09:32.740 --> 09:33.707
- Oh, yeah--yeah.
- Yeah.

09:33.741 --> 09:35.108
- Is this annoying?

09:35.142 --> 09:36.710
Oh, oh, oh.
- Okay, yeah, yeah.

09:36.744 --> 09:38.045
Okay, thank you.

09:38.078 --> 09:39.613
- Am I freaking you guys out?

09:39.647 --> 09:42.750
Because I'm like,
"Oh-ahh, I love you guys,"

09:42.783 --> 09:45.285
and you're like,
"Ooh, she's weird."

09:45.318 --> 09:46.787
- No, no.
- No.

09:46.820 --> 09:50.290
- I just--she has somewhere
that we have to be.

09:50.323 --> 09:52.793
- Of course.
I know how busy you guys are.

09:52.826 --> 09:54.795
(suspenseful music)
What's that over there?

09:54.828 --> 09:56.463
*

09:56.496 --> 09:57.731
- Did you just cut her hair?

09:57.765 --> 10:00.133
- I really am
your number one fan.

10:00.167 --> 10:01.568
(melodramatic music)

10:01.601 --> 10:02.569
- Whoa-ooh...

10:02.602 --> 10:05.739
- Ugh...
- What the hell?

10:05.773 --> 10:07.407
Josh, some of these
letters from your mom

10:07.440 --> 10:09.142
are really unhinged.
- It's not that bad.

10:09.176 --> 10:11.578
- This one keeps referencing
the day we become one.

10:11.611 --> 10:13.313
- Well, we just--
we won't reply to that one.

10:13.346 --> 10:15.448
- In this one, she drew
Christ upside-down on the cross.

10:15.482 --> 10:17.250
- She's just being a mother.

10:17.284 --> 10:19.619
- This one's three tickets
for us to see "Jersey Boys."

10:19.653 --> 10:20.754
(exhales)

10:20.788 --> 10:23.757
(intense percussive music)

10:23.791 --> 10:25.793
*

